Hi, my name is Kim Donaldson. Thanks for reviewing my capstone project for the Google Data Analytics Professional Certificate. Im excited to put what Ive learned to good use. I chose the bellabeat case study because I have an interest in fitness. As I have been going through the coursework on coursera I have not been excercising as much. So, I hope to not only find interesting insights that could be applied to business products, but also some inspiration to get active.

About Bellabeat

Bellabeat is a manufacturer of smart devices for women. Bellabeats mission is to empower women with data to discover themselves. Key Stakeholers include:

  • Urka Sren - Cofounder, Chief Creative Officer
  • Sando Mur - Mathmematician and cofounder
  • Marketing Analytics Team

Scope of work

Analyze fitbit data to gain insights into how smart devices are used and provide key insights to help the marketing team make data driven decisions.

  1. Identify trends in smart device usage
  2. Determine how relevant these trends are for Bellabeat customers
  3. Determine how these trends can help guide the Marketing Analytics Team

The Products

  • Bellabeat App - Provides users with data related to activity, sleep, stress, menstrual cycle, and mindfulness habits.
  • Ivy - A health tracker designed to be worn as a bracelet. Measures Steps, active time, calories, distance, active heart rate, and workout intensity, sleep duration, sleep quality, resting heart rate, respitatory rate, and cardiac coherence.
  • Leaf Urban - An elegant health tracker that can be worn as a bracelet, necklace, or clip. Records data to track activity, sleep, stress, and reproductive health.
  • Time - Luxury hybrid wellness watch that track activity, sleep, and stress. Offered in Silver and Rose Gold
  • Spring - Waterbottle that tracks water intake, connects with Bellabeat App
  • Bellabeat Membership - Subscription based program that provides guidance on nutrition activity, sleep, health, beauty, and mindufulness with a focus on lifestyle and goals.
  • Accessories - Includes bracelets, neclaces, water bottles, and yoga mats.

Business Purpose

This case study will focus on finding insights that could grow the number of customers that purchase the Bellabeat+ Club subscription. My hypothesis is that more active people are more likely to purchase the exclusive subscription services. Therefore highly active people can be grouped into two categories: members that are currenst subscribers, and members that are not subscribed.

Looking at TotalDistance and TrackerDistance we can see that most of these values are the same. Tracker Distance should never be greater than TotalDistance. We can look at how many times they contain unique values and check to see if there any errors in the reporting.

case_a <- daily_activity %>% 
  filter(TrackerDistance != TotalDistance)
case_b <- daily_activity %>% 
  filter(TrackerDistance > TotalDistance)

Case A contains 15 obs. This shows that 1.6 percent of the time the total distance isnt completely tracked. Case B contains 0 obs as expected. Im assuming that distance is measured in miles and not kilometers. TotalDistance can be broken down into 4 categories: Very Active, Moderately Active, Lightly Active, and Sedentary Active representing the corresponding intensity levels. When we sort by TotalDistance in Desc order we can see that at least one person tracked an ultra distance of 28.03

Organize by grouping by Id, and sort by active minutes. Clean by selecting only the columns that seem interesting for analysis and transform the date to a standard form.

clean_daily_activity <- daily_activity %>% group_by(Id) %>%
  arrange(-VeryActiveMinutes, -FairlyActiveMinutes, -LightlyActiveMinutes) %>%
  select(Id, ActivityDate, TotalSteps, TotalDistance, VeryActiveMinutes, FairlyActiveMinutes, LightlyActiveMinutes, Calories)

clean_daily_activity <- daily_activity %>% mutate(
  Date = as.Date(mdy(ActivityDate))) %>% select(-ActivityDate)

num_members <- n_distinct(clean_daily_activity$Id) # 33 particiapnts

This shows that Lightly Active Minutes are the most common. Lets look closer at relationship between activity intensities minutes.

active_intensities_t <- clean_daily_activity %>% group_by(Id) %>%
  summarize(avg_very_active_t = mean(VeryActiveMinutes), 
            avg_fair_active_t = mean(FairlyActiveMinutes),
            avg_light_active_t = mean(LightlyActiveMinutes),
            avg_sed_active_t = mean(SedentaryMinutes)
            ) %>% 
  arrange(-avg_very_active_t)

Sleep Data

  • Remove the timestamp and rename the column.
  • Create a new column with proportion of sleep time.
clean_sleep_day <- sleep_day %>% mutate(Date = as.Date(mdy_hms(SleepDay))) %>%
  select(-SleepDay, -TotalSleepRecords)

clean_sleep_day <- clean_sleep_day %>% mutate(PropSleep = TotalMinutesAsleep / TotalTimeInBed) %>%
  select(Id, Date, PropSleep)

I want to see if there is a positive correlation between step count and sleep quality.

step_sleep <- merge(clean_daily_activity, clean_sleep_day, by = c("Id", "Date"))
step_sleep <- step_sleep %>% select(TotalSteps, TotalDistance, PropSleep)

Visualize

ggplot(data = step_sleep) +
  aes(x = TotalSteps, y = PropSleep, color = PropSleep) +
  geom_smooth() + 
  geom_point() + 
  labs(title = "Sleep Quality vs. Step Count", x = "Step Count", y = "Sleep Quality", 
       color = "Sleep Quality")
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

ggplot(data = step_sleep) +
  aes(x = TotalDistance, y = PropSleep, color = PropSleep) +
  geom_smooth() +
  geom_point() + 
  #theme(legend.title = "Sleep Quality") +
  labs(title = "Sleep Quality vs. Distance", x = "Distance", y = "Sleep Quality", 
       color = "Sleep Quality")
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

This shows that with 15,000 steps or about 7 miles per day there is a positive increase in sleep quality. This information could help Bellabeat+ members set goals to improve their quality of sleep.

boston_results <- rbind(clean_br_2015, clean_br_2016, clean_br_2017)
ggplot(boston_results) +
  aes(x = MF, fill = MF) +
  geom_bar() +
  labs(title = "Boston Marathon 2015 - 2017", subtitle = "Female / Male Participation", x = "Gender", fill = "Gender") +
  facet_wrap(~Year)
